:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/17C75998-799E-4F24-AA13-09B334BB5F8E"><gtr:id>17C75998-799E-4F24-AA13-09B334BB5F8E</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Sheila</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Riddell</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FK00705X%2F1"><gtr:id>C5EEAC50-1431-4042-9D6E-37D63DC286C5</gtr:id><gtr:title>Higher Education in Scotland, the Devolution Settlement and the Referendum on Independence</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/K00705X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Higher education is at the centre of the debate on Scottish independence, since this area of social policy has a strong bearing on social justice, individual life chances and social mobility. Scottish policy on the funding of higher education and on widening participation will be examined. Other relevant areas of public policy, such as immigration and employment, will also be explored. The future of shared services, including UCAS and the UK Research Councils will be investigated, as will the future of UK organisations with Scottish branches such as the NUS and the UCU.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>During the course of the project, UCAS data will be used to explore the cross-border flow of students between Scotland, the rest of the UK and Europe. Key informant interviews will be used to examine different visions of the future of Scottish higher education. Public engagement activities will include a series of think tanks and research briefings. There will be a particular focus on hearing the views of young people and a short film and teaching materials will be produced.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:potentialImpactText>Who will benefit from the fellowship?
We envisage that the research findings, knowledge exchange events and outputs of this research will be of interest and use to a very wide audience, including the following:
(1) University, college and school students and staff and the general public;
(2) Organisations and projects with an interest in widening access to education to promote social mobility, such as the the Scottish Funding Council Access and Inclusion Committee, the RAISE project at the University of Glasgow and the LEAPS project at the University of Edinburgh, the Sutton Trust and the Independent Commission on Fees;
(3) Children in Scotland, Commissions for Children and Young People in the different parts of the UK, the Scottish Youth Parliament and the Equality and Human Rights Commission;
(4) Communities of practice such as widening access officers and disabled students' advisers
(5)Trades unions such as the UCU, the EIS, the TUC and the STUC;
(6)The National Union of Students;
(7) Civil servants across the UK and European Commission staff (e.g. those in DG-EAC)
(8) Arms-length agencies operating in the devolved administrations and at UK level such as the Office for Fair Access, UCAS, the UK Border Agency, the Funding Councils and the Quality Assurance Agency.
(9) Academics in education, social policy, politics, equality, law and employment.

How will they benefit from this fellowship?
The groups identified above will benefit from the fellowship in the following ways:
(1) Access to well researched working papers and briefings which will provide essential information to inform the debate on independence;
(2) The opportunity to attend a range of stimulating and participatory events. We aim to involve policy-makers, academics, the general public and younger people, particularly those who are first time voters, with the aim of increasing knowledge of the key issues. 
(3) Younger people will be encouraged to engage with the issues through events and outputs designed with their interests in mind. These include the final glossy publication, resource materials, a short film and a podcast; 
(4) Policy-makers, academics, the general public and young people will be interested in the analysis of UCAS data since 1996, which provides insight into cross-border student flows under devolution and possible future trends following independence.</gtr:potentialImpactText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2014-07-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2013-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>306210</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutput><gtr:description>One of the aims of the project is to promote the engagement of young people in the independence debate. The film, Our Future: Young People's Views on Higher Education in Scotland, involves discussions with young people aged 14 to 17, from Edinburgh, Fife, Glasgow, the Western Isles and West Lothian; in total, 89 young people participated in making the film. It is available to view either in full (20 minutes) or as five individual sections: 
- Part 1: Introduction and the benefits of HE
- Part 2: Funding of HE
- Part 3: Cross border flow of students
- Part 4: Widening access to HE
- Part 5: The referendum on independence.</gtr:description><gtr:id>DBA33C77-DB02-4416-AB3A-CF0D3F4A461C</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The teaching materials and a copy of the DVD were sent to all secondary schools in Scotland (approximately 400 schools). It was previewed to policy makers and practitioners at our third think tank in January 2014, and was also available to view on Youtube. The 20 minute version of the full length film has been viewed 537 times (73% of these were outside the UK). It was also available to view as individual clips: 
? Part 1, including the introduction and a discussion of the benefits of HE has been viewed 115 times (67% of views were in the UK)
? Part 2 on funding 99 times (53% of views in the UK)
? Part 3 on cross border flow of students 51 times (84% of views in UK)
? Part 4 on widening access 78 times (80% of views in UK)
? Part 5 on young people's views of independence has been viewed 1,255 times (71% of views in UK)

Youtube analytics show that the clips have been viewed predominantly in the UK. Reach outside of the UK has also been significant, with clips viewed in 53 countries: France, Germany, Austria, Sweden, the USA, Switzerland, Belgium, Italy, Australia, Norway, Spain, the Netherlands, Canada, Portugal, Ukraine, Ireland, Mexico, Denmark, Latvia, India, United Arab Emirates, Israel, Estonia, Cyprus, Serbia, Malaysia, Slovakia, Luxembourg, Jamaica, Japan, Taiwan, Bangladesh, Singapore, Hong Kong, Brazil, Indonesia, Turkey, Tunisia, Poland, Peru, Chile, Philippines, Azerbaijan, Croatia, Nepal, South Korea, Sweden, Bulgaria, Slovenia, Jordan, Saudi Arabia, Vietnam and Greece. The clip of the full film reached the widest selection of countries outside of the UK (38 in total). Analytics show that views of Part 5 on young people's views of the referendum increased greatly in the week of the referendum. Almost half (47%) of views of Part 2 on funding were from outside the UK. 

The film was shown to social researchers at the Scottish Government as part of a discussion on methodological issues of filming young people. We had the following response about this on 21 August 2014: 
Hi Sarah,
Thank you for coming in this week, in spite of the technical hitches we've had good feedback from those who were there. I watched the Youtube version at home last night to see the whole thing, really it is excellent. Would you mind if we showed it, or part of it at our Away Day to all of our researchers, as I think it's a really good chance to hear directly from people who were research subjects rather than just statistics. I'm not sure what the copyright etc. would be, so if that's an issue for you of course I understand if it's not possible. (We'll be out of the office, so youtube available!)
Best regards
Graeme
