As a result of sharing information about publications, seminars and blogs, the work of the project has reached a greater number of people, and a wider, more diverse audience. While many Twitter followers are organisations and academics, we also have a number of unaffiliated followers. The Twitter feed has been used as a means of reaching a wider audience with news of the project and its outputs, and it has helped to disseminate our materials much further than we would otherwise have reached.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>545cbea95f2676.86958764</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>https://twitter.com/Indy_Scot_HE</gtr:url><gtr:year>2013,2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Press release to accompany Seminar 1 on HE funding: 'Edinburgh team launch work on Scottish HE's future', 20 May 2013</gtr:description><gtr:form>A press release, press conference or response to a media enquiry/interview</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>C434E4EE-A250-4531-B25F-A26B40138581</gtr:id><gtr:impact>A press release (Edinburgh team launch work on Scottish HE's future, 20 May 2013) accompanied Seminar 1 on the future financing of Scottish higher education. This was released in advance of the seminar on 22 May 2013 which was attended by around 60 academics, policy makers and journalists, including a BBC film crew. 

The press release was picked up on and reported by a number of newspapers, many of which concentrated on Professor David Bell's presentation which explored the potential for increased numbers of students from the rest of the UK coming to study in an independent Scotland.

CREID's first seminar as part of Professor Sheila Riddell's ESRC Fellowship generated a large amount of coverage in the press and broadcast media. And Professor Riddell's work was cited in a question at First Minister's Questions and was directly commented on by Education Secretary Mike Russell. 

Press coverage included:
1) Chris Marshall (2013) Scottish independence - Scots students could suffer, The Scotsman, 22 May 2013, http://www.scotsman.com/news/education/scottish-independence-scots-s</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>545b84c67739a1.24097058</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Media (as a channel to the public)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.research.ed.ac.uk/portal/en/clippings/edinburgh-team-launch-work-on-scottish-hes-future%284a66ba06-0b4a-48bd-82d3-56ecaa441258%29.html</gtr:url><gtr:year>2013</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Seminar 5: The future of higher education in Scotland and the UK, University of Edinburgh, 29 January 2014</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>33BCC459-E6C5-4EF4-A9BB-504FE88B40A6</gtr:id><gtr:impact>172 people attended the event held at the University of Edinburgh on 29 January 2014. The seminar concerned the future of higher education, and explored different policy futures for Scotland, patterns of cross-border student flows and how this might change in the future depending on the nature of constitutional change, the future of research funding and the impact of constitutional change on those who work in Scottish universities. This was a high profile event, with both Michael Russell, Cabinet Secretary for Education and Lifelong Learning, Scottish Government and Alistair Carmichael, Secretary of State for Scotland speaking at the event to present their alternative visions for Scottish HE. The event was chaired by Professor Charlie Jeffery. Other speakers included Sir Andrew Cubie, Professor Anton Muscatelli (University of Glasgow), Professor Susan Robertson (University of Bristol), Dave Watson (Unison), Mary Senior (UCU) and David Lott (Universities Scotland). Sarah Minty also showed a preview of the Our Future film at the event (see separate Engagement Activity entry).

The event was accompanied by both a press release and a pre-event briefing (see separate Engagement Activity entry).

The seminar generated a lot of debate at the event itself, and in the wider media, for example it was covered by the BBC (see separate engagement activity entry).

Sarah Minty live-tweeted from the event, and the audience was encouraged to use #HEScot. This was very successful, and there were 387 tweets using this hashtag between 28 January and 3 November, with 338 tweets on the day of the event 87 users. Sarah Minty created a Storify for the event on 4 February to chart some of the Twitter engagement with the seminar which can be viewed at https://storify.com/futureukscot/higher-education-scotland-event. It has been viewed 236 times. This helped to promo</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>545cae83590e85.07953440</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Policymakers/politicians</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.ed.ac.uk/schools-departments/education/rke/centres-groups/creid/news-events/events-in-2013/esrc-fellowship-seminar</gtr:url><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Professor Raffe's comments in the TESS in response to LSE research report, 'Education in a Devolved Scotland: A Quantitative Analysis Report to the ESRC (Special Paper No. 30)'</gtr:description><gtr:form>A press release, press conference or response to a media enquiry/interview</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>C2900FFD-A8BD-422E-98EF-B2667FD60A3A</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Emma Seith wrote an article for the TESS on 9 August ('CfE has an edge on independence, academic claims', http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storycode=6347210), which includes an interview with Professor Raffe. Asked to respond to a report by Machin, McNally and Wyness (2013, &amp;quot;Education in a Devolved Scotland: A Quantitative Analysis - Report to the ESRC, March 2013, Special Paper No. 30, http://cep.lse.ac.uk/pubs/download/special/cepsp30.pdf), Professor Raffe noted that factors such as the class system, peer pressure and the way people perceive opportunities were more important than money in attributing inequalities to education. The articles states: 

'But inequalities in education are a reflection of wider society and too deeply rooted for money to be able to do much more than tinker round the edges, Professor Raffe said. 
&amp;quot;How money is spent does make a difference, but when it comes to inequalities it can only make a difference at the margins,&amp;quot; he added. &amp;quot;There are more important factors driving inequalities - the class system, peer pressure, the way people perceive opportunities.&amp;quot;
The Nordic countries and the Netherlands had reduced inequalities and an independent Scotland could conceivably &amp;quot;go down the Nordic route in terms of social policy&amp;quot;, which would have a knock-on effect for education, Professor Raffe said. But whether the Scottish government would choose to take that path - or be able to - was &amp;quot;a big if&amp;quot;, he said.
Curriculum for Excellence was more likely to influence educational outcomes in Scotland than independence, he said.'

The Scotsman also reported Professor Raffe's comments in response to the LSE report: Education 'has failed to improve with devolution', 15 August, http://www.scotsman.com/news/education/education-has-failed-to-improve-with-devolution-1-3046489:

'Professor David Raffe, of the Centre for Educational Sociology at Edinburgh University, said: &amp;quot;It's fair to say education has not improved greatly [since devolution]. Devolution has not made a difference to the rate of progress.

&amp;quot;Curriculum for Excellence is creating a divergence between the English and Scottish systems, and that does mean that in ten years' time, the types of learning could potentially look a bit more different. But it's going to take some time before the changes filter through.&amp;quot;'</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>545bb548f06816.02543562</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Media (as a channel to the public)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storycode=6347210</gtr:url><gtr:year>2013</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Presentation by Weedon E to a group of visiting Chinese lecturers from Ningxia University in China (University of Edinburgh, 10th Aug 2016)</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>17232140-8123-4B36-82C6-5A29112FE42D</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Dr Elisabet Weedon was invited by the International Office of the University of Edinburgh to give a talk on widening access in the UK and Europe to a group of visiting Chinese lecturers from Ningxia University in China. Elisabet's presentation &amp;quot;Widening access and higher education in Europe and the UK&amp;quot; can be accessed via this link</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>5899cdec8cbd35.72459233</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.ed.ac.uk/education/rke/centres-groups/creid/news-events/news-archive/news-archive-2016/weedon-ppt-ningxia-wideningaccess-he</gtr:url><gtr:year>2016</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Press release for Seminar 4: 'Student access to higher education in England and Scotland under the spotlight', 3 October 2013</gtr:description><gtr:form>A press release, press conference or response to a media enquiry/interview</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>4E4058D2-AB96-44B6-9216-721A1BF3AF0F</gtr:id><gtr:impact>A press release, 'Student access to higher education in England and Scotland under the spotlight', was published on 3 October 2013, in advance of Seminar 4: Widening access to higher education - Scotland in UK comparative context. This was also accompanied by a pre-event briefing paper which outlined the key themes to be covered on the day. The press release and the briefing attracted a lot of interest, with news of the seminar run in all the key Scottish daily newspapers. The majority of reports concentrated on the argument that free tuition has not led to wider access to HE for those from disadvantaged backgrounds.

In advance of the seminar, Professor Riddell also had an article published in the letters sections of the Holyrood Magazine, which summarised the key themes to be discussed at the ESRC Fellowship seminar, held on the 8th October, 2013 (Major questions over university access, Holyrood Magazine, 7 October 2013, http://www.docs.hss.ed.ac.uk/education/creid/Press/20131007_HolyroodMagazine_Major-Qs-over-university-access.pdf)

