To be confirmed</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>543bfc600d9c71.50869944</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Other academic audiences (collaborators, peers etc.)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.sera.ac.uk/documents/2014/SERA-WERA_2014_Conference_Programme.pdf</gtr:url><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Riddell's and Blackburn's remarks in the News Statesman, 12 April 2016</gtr:description><gtr:form>A press release, press conference or response to a media enquiry/interview</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>43095390-164F-4B90-8DCA-F8AC1B7FA035</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Tim Wigmore wrote an article for the News Statement on 12 April ('The SNP has failed Scotland's children', ), which quoted remarks of Riddell and Blackburn on the failure of free university tuition in Scotland to narrow the attainment gap between advantaged and less advantaged Scottish children and to widen access to higher education for the latter. The article states:

'Since devolution, there is no policy that the SNP trumpet more proudly than resisting the move to tuition fees south of the border, and keeping university education completely free of charge. This is flaunted as a triumph of progressive politics: Sturgeon likes to say that fees would have prevented her from going to university.

Yet protecting Scottish students from university tuition fees has led to cuts to student grants, and a &amp;pound;20 million transfer from disadvantaged students to middle-class ones, according to the policy analyst Lucy Hunter Blackburn. The poorer you are in Scotland, the greatest the debt when you graduate: students from households that earn less than &amp;pound;34,000 will typically graduate with between &amp;pound;4,000 to &amp;pound;5,000 more debt than those from families earning more, research from Hunter Blackburn shows. 

The tuition fee policy has also hurt disadvantaged students in another way. Success rates for Scots applying to university have fallen sharply in recent years, and are now well below those for applicants in England or Wales, due to the relatively tight cap on the number of students that Scottish universities can take. This hurts all students but disproportionately affects the most disadvantaged. Meanwhile in England the cap on the number of students universities can take has been removed, benefiting all students but especially the most disadvantaged.

The deleterious consequences of free university tuition extend to school education. &amp;quot;Higher education spending has been maintained whilst spending on schools and colleges has been cut. This is a conscious political decision,&amp;quot; says Sheila Riddell from the University of Edinburgh. The effects can be seen in the investment in schools. Between 2010 and 2013, school spending in Scotland fell by five per cent in real terms from 2010 to 2013 while, in England, it rose by three per cent in real terms between 2010 and 2015.

If the extra cuts forced by the maintenance of free tuition fees are one common theme of Scotland's educational problems, there is another striking one: a lack of accountability. The culture of ubiquitous school league tables is lacking north of Berwick-upon-Tweed.

Scottish education needs &amp;quot;a more robust evidence base,&amp;quot; the OECD report noted, while the Social Mobility and Child Poverty Commission have said the lack of data impedes analysis of &amp;quot;the effectiveness of different policy interventions at improving social mobility&amp;quot;. It is not merely a bureaucratic issue. &amp;quot;A lack of data means a lack of accountability,&amp;quot; Riddell says. The reluctance to use data to highlight failings in schools partly explains why Scotland has also shied away from the educational reforms that have been pioneered in London and then rolled out in the rest of England, including the Teach First programme and academies.'</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>571a057b583bf9.11166934</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Media (as a channel to the public)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/04/snp-has-failed-scotlands-children</gtr:url><gtr:year>2006</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Seminar 6: Our Future: what do young people think about Scottish higher education and independence? Seminar for school pupils, University of Edinburgh, 11 June 2014</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Regional</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>156BCA57-41E3-4680-B956-0531211D0DDC</gtr:id><gtr:impact>115 young people from S5 and S6 from ten schools in the central belt attended the event. Some of the schools had been involved in the research, while others were new to the project. Twenty undergraduate students from Dallas, Texas, who were visiting Edinburgh as part of their studies also attended, having heard about the event from a colleague.

The event was chaired by Dr Rowena Arshad, Head of School at Moray House School of Education. Presenters included team members Sarah Minty, Professor Riddell and Susan Whittaker, as well as Dr Jan Eichhorn from AQMeN who discussed findings of his related research of a survey of 14-17 year old's voting intentions. The aim of the day was to feed back findings of the research with young people, and to provide space for pupils to debate some of the issues with their peers. Five short presentations were interspersed with clips from the Our Future film, and an electronic voting system (known as 'clickers') was used to gauge opinion of young people on the day and to see how that compared to the views of those reported in the research. 

After lunch, pupils were invited to attend three break-out sessions which allowed participants to discuss some of the issues with their peers and then feed back to the floor. At the end of the day, a panel discussion pulled together some of the issues. Panellists included Professor Riddell, Sarah Minty, Gary Paterson (a Member of the Scottish Youth Parliament), and two sixth year students - Ramsay from St Joseph's Academy, and Alicia from Douglas Academy in Bearsden.

The event was very well received, and feedback from pupils was particularly positive about the clips from the Our Future film and use of the 'clickers'. Students from the US and Scotland mixed together well and appeared to enjoy the chance to learn about one another's educational systems. In terms of areas for improvement, pupils requested fewer statistics, while teachers hoped for greater integration with the Modern Studies curriculum and exams.

