:form>A magazine, newsletter or online publication</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>225125D7-BD9E-46DC-941C-ADD6DC0EF38B</gtr:id><gtr:impact>One of the aims of the project was to promote the engagement of young people in the independence debate. As part of this a film was produced, 'Our Future: Young People's Views on Higher Education in Scotland', which includes interviews with young people aged 14 to 17, from Edinburgh, Fife, Glasgow, the Western Isles and West Lothian. A copy of the DVD was sent to all Scottish secondary schools (approximately 400 schools) in early January 2014, accompanied by a set of teaching materials with ideas and activities to encourage discussion among young voters on the future of higher education. 

The film was also available to view on Youtube (full version at: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Alc1XzblgpE). It was available to watch either in full (20 minutes) or in five shorter sections: Part 1: Introduction and the benefits of HE; Part 2: Funding of HE; Part 3: Cross border flow of students; Part 4: Widening access to HE; Part 5: The referendum on independence.

Sarah Minty wrote a blog to accompany the launch of the film and teaching materials for the Future of the UK and Scotland website, 'Our Future: Young people's views on higher education and independence in Scotland': http://www.futureukandscotland.ac.uk/blog/our-future-young-people%E2%80%99s-views-higher-education-and-independence-scotland. The blog was viewed 247 times and by 205 unique users. 

The film and teaching materials were featured as resources for teachers on a number of websites including: 

? ESRC Social Science for Schools website: 'Resources from the Future of the UK and Scotland programme': 
http://www.socialscienceforschools.org.uk/resources/UK-and-Scotland/resources.aspx 
