Two articles from the Guardian (29th April 2014) and an article from Huffington Post (1st May 2014) cited Lucy Hunter Blackburn's working paper for the ESRC Fellowship project. While noting that free tuition and cuts to grants in Scotland mainly benefit more affluent families, the articles also highlighted the benefits of the Welsh unique loan system to lower-income families. Anna Rawden and Abby Young-Powell's article 'Welsh university students get most financial support in UK' (http://www.docs.hss.ed.ac.uk/education/creid/Press/20140429_Guardian_Welsh-univ-students-get-most-financial-support-in-UK.pdf) was published in The Guardian on the same day (29 April 2014) as Severin Carrell's article, also for The Guardian, 'Free tuition in Scotland benefits wealthiest students the most' (http://www.docs.hss.ed.ac.uk/education/creid/Press/20140429_Guardian_Free-tuition-in-Scotland-benefits-wealthiest-students-the-most.pdf). The articles include Lucy's comments as well as responses from Education Minister Michael Russell and Kezia Dugdale (MSP). The following day, The Huffington Post UK also ran a similar story, focusing on the generous Welsh funding system, 'Welsh Students Get The Most Financial Support For Tuition Fees In The UK' (1 May 2014, http://www.docs.hss.ed.ac.uk/education/creid/Press/20140502_HuffPost_Welsh-Students-Get-the-Most-Financial-Support-for-Tuition-Fees-in-the-UK.pdf)</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>545cbb048d5651.08114206</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Media (as a channel to the public)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.docs.hss.ed.ac.uk/education/creid/Projects/34ii_d_ESRCF_WP3.pdf</gtr:url><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Seminar 2: Changing inequalities and access to a differentiated higher education system, 14 June 2013.</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>580137FB-CEBB-4AE3-890A-45DAB98B90A8</gtr:id><gtr:impact>50 delegates attended the event from a range of backgrounds, including researchers, policy makers and practitioners, as well as journalists. A press release and two briefing papers were also published to coincide with the event. 

The seminar presented findings from a study of changing patterns of application and entry to higher education using UCAS data between 1996 and 2010. The study compared England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland over the first full decade since devolution, and examined trends in cross-border movements. The seminar was chaired by Emeritus Professor Sally Brown, and included presentations from Professor Raffe and Dr Croxford, and a plenary discussion which included Professor Riddell, Mark Ratho of the Scottish Funding Council, and Professor Gareth Rees from WISERD. The seminar provided an opportunity for delegates to discuss the findings and their implications for policy and practice, and generated a lot of questions and discussions during the plenary session.

