The blog contributed to the wider public debate in the lead up to the referendum.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>543f9bbe822865.88128391</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.futureukandscotland.ac.uk/blog/state-debate-higher-education</gtr:url><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>17149</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>ESRC Impact Grant</gtr:description><gtr:end>2015-09-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Economic and Social Research Council</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>8F40CF79-278A-43A0-AC71-609920CF243C</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>545b84fc83c373.08421640</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2014-10-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Our findings have made a major contribution to the debate on Scottish independence and UK constitutional change. Analysis of cross-border student flows fed into discussions of the impact of different funding regimes across the UK, including the Welsh Government's Review of Higher Education Funding and Student Finance Arrangements in Wales. Key informant interviews contributed to discussion of the core values of Scottish HE in comparison with other UK systems. Interviews with young people fed in to the production of school pupils in the constitutional debate. Research findings were discussed in a series of knowledge exchange events, featured in newspaper articles and television debates. Our work has also contributed to policy development across the UK, for example, including citation in the Annual Report of the Child Poverty and Social Mobility Commission 2014 . As a member of the review of higher education in Wales, chaired by Professor Sir Ian Diamond, Professor Sheila Riddell provided evidence on cross-border students flows and the influence of fees regimes to widening access. Professor David Raffe provided evidence to UK and Scottish Government higher education policy committees, as well as producing a report on university governance for the Leadership Foundation (see below for further details). Lucy Hunter Blackburn, an associate member of the team, was commissioned to write a rep[ort for the Higher education policy Institute entitled 'Whose to lose? Citizens, institutions and the ownership of higher education funding in a devolved UK' (Published February 2015). Sarah Minty was awarded an ESRC impact accelerator award by the University of Edinburgh to produce a publication aimed at raising students' awareness of issues associated with the financing of higher education. This work was conducted in association with NUS Scotland and the Students Award Agency for Scotland.</gtr:description><gtr:id>384FF266-930D-4CEA-937F-7A867B29D031</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural,Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>543bf7e55f9f71.43786827</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Education,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>(1) Our research analysed the development of higher education policy since devolution, exploring the extent of policy convergence and divergence. This analysis underlined both the strengths and weaknesses of the existing devolution settlement, which allowed each country to pursue distinctive policies, but without placing any limits on the extent of divergence or the knock-on effects of each country's policies on those of its neighbours. The research also analysed the way in which higher education featured in the independence debate, including the way in which it was used to support particular constitutional positions. For example, in the White Paper, the Scottish Government argued that undergraduate fees policy illustrated fundamental social policy differences between England and Scotland, with Scotland adopting a universalist approach to welfare provision, whilst English higher education was increasingly driven by the market and individual student choice. The unionist parties, on the other hand, argued that higher education illustrated the virtues of devolution, so that within the existing constitutional arrangements Scotland was able to maintain a distinctive approach to undergraduate student funding, whilst benefitting from membership of the UK higher education research area.

(2) Interviews with Scottish policy makers suggested that the majority welcomed particular aspects of higher education policy, in particular the approach to undergraduate student funding. However, they questioned its sustainability in the light of ongoing austerity within the public sector, and believed that it was driven by politics rather than fundamental differences in core values. English policy makers were divided, some questioning the sustainability of the English approach to student fees, repayable via income contingent repayment systems, whilst supporting the decision of Scottish policy makers to fund student fees through the block grant. On the other hand, growing differences in territorial social entitlements, exemplified in higher education, were seen as problematic.

(3) Young people in Scotland also supported the policy of enabling Scottish-domiciled students to study without incurring tuition fees, but like the policy makers, questioned its sustainability. Young people in the north of England believed that the policy was unfair, arguing that UK citizens should have equivalent social entitlements irrespective of residence. All of our interviewees believed that major changes in higher education policy across the UK were likely, irrespective of the referendum outcome. 

(4) Analysis of HESA data revealed connections between student fees policy and cross-border student flows, since different policies may incentivise or disincentivise student movement. Overall, there has been a small decline in the number of Scottish students studying in another home country since devolution. By way of contrast, Welsh-domiciled students are more likely to study in another part of the UK, since student fee support provided by the Welsh Government is transportable. Population projections suggest that there will be a decline in the number of young people in Scotland until about 2023. In order to sustain the size of its higher education sector, it will be necessary for Scotland to be able to attract a growing number of young people from the EU, rest of the UK and internationally.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>As constitutional change progresses, it will be important to examine patterns of policy convergence and divergence in higher education policy across the UK. In particular, it will be important to analyse the extent to which there is a continuation of the distinctiveness of HE policy across the four countries of the UK. Conversely, the impact of internationalisation and globalisation, as well as the politics of austerity, may produce greater uniformity. The work on cross-border student flows provides an important benchmark against which future changes may be measured.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>4CB6D343-988E-43E3-A8F6-C0EDAC573FAF</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>543c01cc210286.86103701</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Education,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.ed.ac.uk/schools-departments/education/rke/centres-groups/creid/projects/he-in-scotland/he-in-scotland</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs><gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:areas/><gtr:description>Citation in Universities Scotland Annual Report Evidence Submission to Social Mobilit