Paragraph 90 on page 221 cites Riddell, S., Raffe, D., Croxford, L., Weedon, E., and Minty, S. (2013) Widening Access to Higher Education: Scotland in UK Comparative Context under reference 104: 
'90. Emerging evidence suggests that the poorest graduates leave university with more debt than more advantaged graduates. From 2013/14 maintenance grants have been reduced and student loans increased, resulting in the highest student debt for those from the lowest income backgrounds. (ref 102) Grants for the poorest students (those from families earning less than &amp;pound;16,000 per year) have been reduced by about one-third from &amp;pound;2,650 in 2012/13 to &amp;pound;1,750 in 2014/15. Grants for mature students have historically been lower and these have reduced from &amp;pound;1,000 in 2012/2013 to &amp;pound;750 in 2014/15. Calculations show that the poorest young people will have to borrow &amp;pound;23,000. Scottish students do not necessarily graduate with less debt than all other parts of the UK. Recent research states that &amp;quot;even in the absence of tuition fees, levels of final debt for low-income Scottish students who study in Scotland are comparable with and, in certain cases, higher than debt levels for similar students from the other devolved administrations&amp;quot;. (Refs 103, 104)'

The citation in the report led Ross Neilson from the Social Mobility and Child Poverty Commission to contact members of the research team inviting them to a meeting to discuss the availability of Scottish data on access to HE and attainment for the most disadvantaged young people.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>544776f16fb876.88296741</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:type>Citation in other policy documents</gtr:type><gtr:url>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-of-the-nation-2014-report</gtr:url></gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:policyInfluenceOutput><gtr:areas/><gtr:description>Sarah Minty's evidence to the Scottish Government's Education and Culture Committee's inquiry into student support</gtr:description><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>C63AD26F-81A7-40EF-87B1-B067C5A7569A</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Following some press coverage on the research of Lucy Hunter Blackburn and Sarah Minty on student finance and the production of a student finance guide by Sarah Minty, Sarah Minty submitted an evidence paper, alongside another evidence paper submitted by Lucy Hunter Blackburn, to the Education and Culture Committee of the Scottish Government in response to its inquiry into living cost support for students through bursaries and loans.

